# Blurring Image
import numpy as np
from scipy import ndimage
from skimage.data import camera

image = camera()

kernel = 1/245*np.array([ [1, 4, 6, 4, 1], 
                        [4, 16, 24, 16, 4], 
                        [6, 24, 36, 24, 6],
                        [4, 16, 24, 16, 4],
                        [1, 4, 6, 4, 1]]) 

filtered = ndimage.convolve(image, kernel, mode='constant', cval=0.0)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols=2, sharex=True, sharey=True,
                       figsize=(10, 10))

ax[0].imshow(image, cmap=plt.cm.gray)
ax[0].set_title('Original')

ax[1].imshow(filtered, cmap=plt.cm.gray)
ax[1].set_title('Gaussian Blur 5x5')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

#Sharpen image
kernel = np.array([ [0, -1, 0], 
                    [-1, 6, -1], 
                    [0, -1, 0]])

filtered = ndimage.convolve(image, kernel, mode='mirror', cval=0.0)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols=2, sharex=True, sharey=True,
                       figsize=(10, 10))

ax[0].imshow(image, cmap=plt.cm.gray)
ax[0].set_title('Original')

ax[1].imshow(filtered, cmap=plt.cm.gray)
ax[1].set_title('Sharpen convolution')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

#EDGE 1
kernel_edge = np.array([ [1, 0, -1], 
                       [0, 0, 0], 
                        [-1, 0, 1]])


edge = ndimage.convolve(image, kernel_edge, mode='mirror', cval=0.0)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols=2, sharex=True, sharey=True,
                       figsize=(10, 10))

ax[0].imshow(image, cmap=plt.cm.gray)
ax[0].set_title('Original')

ax[1].imshow(edge, cmap=plt.cm.gray)
ax[1].set_title('Edge convolution')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

#EDGE 2: GAUSSIAN + EDGE
kernel_gaussian = 1/256*np.array([ [1, 4, 6, 4, 1], 
                        [4, 16, 24, 16, 4], 
                        [6, 24, 36, 24, 6],
                        [4, 16, 24, 16, 4],
                        [1, 4, 6, 4, 1]]) 

kernel_edge = np.array([ [1, 0, -1], 
                       [0, 0, 0], 
                        [-1, 0, 1]])



filtered = ndimage.convolve(image, kernel_gaussian, mode='mirror', cval=0.0)
edge = ndimage.convolve(filtered, kernel_edge, mode='mirror', cval=0.0)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols=3, sharex=True, sharey=True,
                       figsize=(10, 10))

ax[0].imshow(image, cmap=plt.cm.gray)
ax[0].set_title('Original')

ax[1].imshow(filtered, cmap=plt.cm.gray)
ax[1].set_title('Gaussian convolution')

ax[2].imshow(edge, cmap=plt.cm.gray)
ax[2].set_title('Gaussian plus edge convolution')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# EXERCISE 2: image segmentation [OBLIGATORY]

Take a picture with your phone or your camera of some objects that you want to count. (Beware: try to take high contrast images with a stable background).

* Load the image with scikit image
* Count the objects in the image using region based segmentation
* Try to fix the image using opening/closing algorithms

from skimage.io import imread,imshow
from skimage import data
from skimage.exposure import histogram
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from skimage.color import rgb2gray

photo = imread('/Users/jorgesalazar/Downloads/IMG_6936 2.jpg')
photobw = rgb2gray(photo)
imshow(photobw)

import numpy as np
from scipy import ndimage
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

hist, hist_centers = histogram(photobw)

# Plotting segmentation
fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols=2, sharex=False, sharey=False,
                       figsize=(11, 4))

ax[0].imshow(photobw, cmap=plt.cm.gray)
ax[0].set_title('Coins')

ax[1].plot(hist_centers, hist)
ax[1].set_title('Histogram of gray values')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

from skimage import data
from skimage.feature import canny
from skimage.filters import sobel



canny_coins = canny(photobw/255.)

sobel_coins = sobel(photobw*1000000)

# Plotting segmentation
fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols=2, sharex=False, sharey=False,
                       figsize=(11, 4))

ax[0].imshow(canny_coins)
ax[0].set_title('Canny')

ax[1].imshow(sobel_coins)
ax[1].set_title('Sobel')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.imshow(photobw)
plt.colorbar()

# Let's create a zeros array with the same shape as coins
markers = np.zeros_like(photobw)

# When the pixels are over 0.3 (see image above), we can label as background(1)
markers[photobw > 0.2] = 1

# When the pixels are under 0.3 (see image above), we can label as coins(2)
markers[photobw < 0.2] = 2
imshow(markers)

from skimage.morphology import watershed
segmentation = watershed(sobel_coins, markers)
imshow(segmentation)

# Remove the background values before filling!

labeled_coins, _ = ndi.label(segmentation_treshold)
